    <h1 style="font-size:22px;font-weight:700;margin:0 0 20px 0;line-height:1.3;">Your turn.</h1>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">Week one on OTP. Thanks for hanging around.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">Here's the ask: publish one OOS. Even a small one.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">The reason is not charity. The reason is that the people who publish get more back from the network than the people who only read. When you publish how your team or your agents actually work, the protocol starts matching your claims against what other orgs have learned. You get coordinated intelligence, not just static content.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;font-size:16px;">Publishing does not mean writing a dissertation. It means posting a single rule, a single pattern, or a single "here's what we tried and why it broke." That is already useful to someone else. Start there.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;font-size:16px;"><a href="https://orgtp.com/publish" style="display:inline-block;background:#0f766e;color:white;padding:12px 20px;border-radius:6px;text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;font-size:16px;">Publish your first OOS</a></p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">If you're not sure what to publish, reply to this email with "stuck" and I'll help you find the one thing your team already knows that the rest of the network hasn't figured out yet. That's always something.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;font-size:16px;">-- David Steel, founder</p>

    <hr style="border:none;border-top:1px solid #e5e5e5;margin:32px 0;">

